   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>As You
                           Like It</title></hi>]. <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>As You Like It</title>; A Comedy, In Five Acts; By
                                 <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                                 Shakspeare</ref>. As Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. III. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>As You
                              Like It</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Merry Wives of
                              Windsor</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#HenryVIIIKingofEngland">King Henry
                              VIII</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Measure for
                              Measure</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Winter's
                              Tale</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme,
                        Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged at the
                        Globe Theatre in 1599. Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for
                           <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism Archive</hi>. </note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>This comedy has high reputation among <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                  >Shakspeare</ref>'s works; and yet, on the stage, it is never attractive, except
               when some actress, of very superior skill, performs the part of <ref
                  target="people.html#Rosalind">Rosalind</ref>.</p>

            <p>This character requires peculiar talents in representation, because it has so large a
               share of the dialogue to deliver; and the dialogue, though excellently written, and
               interspersed with various points of wit, has still no forcible repartee, or trait of
               humour, which in themselves would excite mirth, independent of an art in giving them
               utterance.</p>

            <p>Such is the general cast of all the other personages in the play, that each requires
               a most skilful actor, to give them their proper degree of importance. </p>

            <p>But, with every advantage to "<title>As you like it</title>" in the performance, it
               is more a pleasing drama, than one which gives delight. The reader will, in general,
               be more charmed than the auditor: for he gains all the poet, which neither the scene
               nor action much adorn, except under particular circumstances.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Dr. Johnson</ref>, in his criticisms at the
               end of this play, gives the following description of it:&#8212;The fable is <fw
                  type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/>wild and pleasing. I
               know not how the ladies will approve the facility with which both <ref
                  target="people.html#Rosalind">Rosalind</ref> and Celia<note><ref
                     target="people.html#Rosalind">Rosalind</ref>'s cousin, the daughter of Duke
                  Frederick. Celia's strong sisterly bond with her cousin causes her to follow <ref
                     target="people.html#Rosalind">Rosalind</ref> into exile.</note> give away their
               hearts. To Celia much may be forgiven, for the heroism of her friendship. The
               character of Jaques<note>Jacques de Bois is the melancholy second son of Sir Rowland
                  de Bois, friend of Duke Senior and enemy of Duke Frederick.</note> is natural, and
               well preserved. The comic dialogue is very sprightly, with less mixture of low
               buffoonery than in some other plays; and the graver part is elegant and
                  harmonious."<note>From <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Samuel
                     Johnson</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Plays of <ref
                           target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakespeare</ref>, In
                        Eight Volumes, With the Corrections and Illustrations of Various
                        Commentators</title></hi> (1765), vol. 2, p. 108.</note></p>

            <p>This must appear but moderate praise to those who may profess to be fervent admirers
               of the comedy. </p>

            <p>Of its origin, <ref target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">Steevens</ref>
                  says&#8212;"<ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> has
               followed <ref target="people.html#LodgeThomas">Lodge</ref>'s novel of
                  "<title>Rosalynd</title>" more exactly than is his general custom, when he is
               indebted to such worthless originals; and has sketched some of his principal
               characters, and borrowed a few expressions from it. It should be observed, however,
               that the characters of Jaques, the Clown, and Audrey,<note>Touchstone, the court
                  jester of Duke Frederick, becomes the love interest of Audrey, an unintelligent
                  country girl.</note> are entirely the poet's own formation."<note>From <ref
                     target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">Steevens</ref>' and <ref
                     target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>The Plays of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                           Shakspeare</ref>, With the Corrections and Illustrations of Various
                        Commentators</title></hi> (1773), vol. 3, p. 229. <ref
                     target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespeare</ref>'s direct source of
                     <hi rendition="#italics"><title>As you Like It</title></hi> is <ref
                     target="people.html#LodgeThomas">Thomas Lodge</ref>'s pastoral romance <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Rosalynde: Euphues Golden Legacie</title></hi>
                  (1590).</note></p>

            <p>The Forest of Arden (or Ardenne), in which the chief scenes of this drama lie, is an
               extensive woody domain, in French Flanders, near the Meuse, and between Charlemont
               and Roeroy.<note>Arden is the name of a forest located near <ref
                     target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespeare</ref>'s home town,
                  Stratford-upon-Avon, but <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                     >Shakespeare</ref> likely had the French forest of the Ardennes in mind, as his
                  source text <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Rosalynde</title></hi> by <ref
                     target="people.html#LodgeThomas">Thomas Lodge</ref> is set in the
                  latter.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> has made the
               inhabitants of this forest appear so happy in their banishment, that, when they are
               called back to the cares of the world, it seems more like a punishment than a reward.
               Jaques has too much prudence to leave his retirement; and yet, when his associates
               are departed, his state can no longer be enviable; as refined society was the charm
               which seemed here to bestow on country life its more than usual enjoyments.</p>
            <pb n="5"/>

            <p><ref target="people.html#KembleJohn">Kemble</ref>'s Jaques is in the highest
               estimation with the public: it is one of those characters in which he gives certain
               bold testimonies of genius, which no spectator can controvert&#8212;yet the mimic art
               has very little share in this grand exhibition. </p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#JordanDorothy">Mrs. Jordan</ref> is the <ref
                  target="people.html#Rosalind">Rosalind</ref> both of art and of nature; each
               supplies its treasures in her performance of the character, and render it a perfect
               exhibition.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
